Ferocity X4<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> This deck attempts to make use of two of the more complex new strategies from the Two Towers, Site Control and discarding Hobbits. First of all lets look at the site path. At first it would seem a little irregular, or slanted against your shadow side, but this couldn’t be less true. The first site, The Riddermark is obviously to Aragorn, beyond that it serves no purpose but to be controlled. Site two has a double purpose though, it provides an early Battleground to control and it hampers my opponents Uruk-Hai. Why not my own you ask? Because I know its there and can play accordingly. Site three is the Barrows of Edoras, I can’t emphasize enough how useful it can be to drop a game ending hand at the bottom of your deck where your sure to draw it at site nine. White Rocks is simple, anti-Rohan and it’s a Battleground. Site five was the hardest of all the sites to decide from. There were effectively two choices for this site, but the single copy of Saruman, Keeper Of Isengard that I ended adding is what decided it. And inevitably my site nine as well. Deeping Wall won the consideration for Saruman’s ability to sit there and threatens to make a ton of Uruks fierce. He can site there alone and stop your opponent from moving. The Caves Oeasterlinglarond is an obvious choice to try to whack the fellowship just before or just after they heal. Site seven, another Battleground and some added archery for the Uruks to throw at the fellowship if the like Unbound companions. Site eight is the only choice possible, because I’m not playing Dunland. The Wizard’s Vale will help keep the twilight high even in a good choke situation. Site nine as mentioned above was dictated by my single copy of Saruman, Keeper Of Isengard. Since you played your site five he should be in your discard pile right, so he ends up playing for two then and you get to drop a bunch of other Uruks down for him to excite into fierceness. Not to mention the site is another Battleground making Ferocity a very useful site nine kill card.<br />
<br />
Now that we’ve covered the sites, let’s cover the bid. As a rule of thumb I like to bid zero to make sure I get my site 2 out to control early. Once I get that Battleground under my control its all gravy. You have enough copies of Aragorn in the deck to get him relatively fast, plus most people will be playing the Riddermark anyway. So to recap, the bid is zero and you’ll want to go second to let you set up a good fellowship hand and get a jump on your site control.<br />
<br />
On to the fellowship. The first thing that you notice is the lack of some of the crap Hobbit cards to encourage discarding. This is countered by simply playing more copies of the given Hobbits. More copies means more chances to pitch the furry footed freaks before you drop an Escape on their asses. Once Escape hits them use the extras to keep them healed up to exert to stealth their skirmishes. There And Back Again keeps them from being overwhelmed in about 50% of most skirmishes also. The only card you want on the Merry and Pippin is Escape, don’t put There and Back Again on them, but drop it on Frodo instead. As he is a Ringbound companion Grima won’t be able to bomb him. Aside from that you have the normal Fordo gear in Sting, Mithril-Coat, and O Elbereth. Aragorn’s card pool in the deck is a little more gear dedicated, but like Legolas and Gimli he discard to his advantage. Aragorn drops the Saga for strength as Legolas drops the Tale, while Gimli drops his helm to avoid wounds and the Hand Axe for archery. Valiant Man Of The West lets Aragorn take two minions and only one wound while Quick As May Be gets rid of those low vitality minions or swarms from Dunland and Moria. With Merry and Pippin both on the table the three hunters can help control the game with ease.<br />
<br />
<br />
The shadow side of the deck is whole different story. It likes to control sites through killing and conditions as well as taking full advantage of the new unloaded keyword Battleground. With Attack On Helm’s Deep and Uruk Stormer as your control engines site control comes easily to this deck. The four Uruk Regulars help get some of the big beef to the table cheaper as well as enhancing that swarm aspect needed by most decks these days to deal with bigger fellowships. There are only four cards directly enhances from site control so the deck is not a diluted site control variant like some you may have seen. Its primary focus is Battleground manipulation. With nine Battleground specific cards in the deck they tend to really want to come out and play harder there. Not to mention if you control a Battleground your Advance Uruk Patrols get very nasty. Your Uruk Captains make these minions even more useful too, as they can play again at a later date. The Palantir will help you burn through some extra twilight to keep Gandalf. The White Wizard weak and vulnerable as well as stall the opponents deck. Broad-Bladed Swords are useful beyond any other weapon Isengard has ever had before. Defend It And Hope? Not going to happen. Gondor Bowmen? Nope. The only real advice here is save them for the big guns you want to get through. Need condition removal? Site control helps here too; with The Burning Of Westfold on the table they can kiss Boromir My Brother and Last Alliance Of Elves And Men goodbye fast. No more super-Faramir to worry about here. Also Isengard has the simplest form of site control there is in the form of Attack On Helm’s Deep. Just play three Uruks and then pitch one in the regroup phase. Simple. And you don’t have to discard it either. Like I said, simple. Then there is the incredibly powerful Ferocity. Unless your opponent is running Legolas Dauntless Hunter and the full Unbound Hobbit party this is the most effective skirmish event for this deck, it may even be better than Savagery because they won’t be able to keep enough companions alive to trigger Savagery’ game text.<br />
<br />
I hope you all can enjoy this deck; it’s been a lot of fun for me to play as well. <br />
